profit, which will probably be for a long time because they are extremely

I thought perhaps "Cabin in the Woods" would kind of end these type of 
movies at least for now, seeing how it so perfectly skewered them and 
subverted the formula. The same way Scream kind of ended the slasher movie 
era.
But apparently not.﻿

Scream didn't "end the slasher movie era". Like with any genre, horror 
films evolve from birth to parody. Wes Craven's Scream was the stage of 
self-reflexive horror (meta-horror). The next stage is roughly parody, 
which means that Scary Movie would be the true "ending of the genre" as you 
describe it.

Luckily genres never truly die out, and the horror genre is a perfect 
example of that because it is such an old genre that keeps coming back. The 
reason why it survives is because of films like these; B-productions often 
keep a genre going until a more innovating, or just refreshing, higher 
budget film makes its debut on the white screen. Examples of the latter can 
include The Conjuring (debatable).

Formulas always get adapted when the box office results prove that they 
need to be, if not they remain what they are for a while. But this 
generally applies to high budget films only; the B-productions feed the 
genre's existence. I don't see why this is a "sad fact" at all. The 
occasional slasher film, or found footage film amuses me and it is my hope 
that the next generations will be able to enjoy them for themselves as well.
